FOR CentOS 7 IMAGE
-------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
Use certbot-auto from https://certbot.eff.org/docs/install.html#operating-system-packages

wget https://dl.eff.org/certbot-auto
chmod a+x ./certbot-auto
sudo ./certbot-auto certonly --standalone --preferred-challenges http --rsa-key-size 4096  -d name.of.server.as.in.OAuth.app

where `name.of.server.as.in.OAuth.app` is the URL of the server you are running.

sudo cp -r /etc/letsencrypt/archive/name.of.server.as.in.OAuth.app .
cp ./name.of.server.as.in.OAuth.app/fullchain.pem ssl.crt
cp ./name.of.server.as.in.OAuth.app/privkey.pem ssl.key

FOR Amazon AMI IMAGE
------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
Amazon's policy does not allow the distribution of licenses on their EC2 free tier servers since the public IP address 
changes every time you stop your instance. 

To bypass this, but still get SSL keys, you can produce your own SSL keys by doing the following.

NOTE: These keys are NOT secure and should not be used outside the realm of testing your server and the Docker capabilities.

openssl req -x509 -newkey rsa:4096 -keyout ssl.key -out ssl.cert -days 365
